[3]
Date: Fri 5 Mar 2004 5:59 AM
From: Mike Nunn <Mike.Nunn@affa.gov.au> [edited]


Anthrax vaccination of troops is in part the subject of a senate
investigation (on 'Current health preparation arrangements for the
deployment of Australian Defence Forces overseas'), but it is early days,
and not much is yet available on this inquiry. The Defence Department's
submission to the inquiry does not mention birth defects. The issues are
more about 'informed consent' and the fact that some troops who declined to
have the vaccine were excluded from undertaking duties: some were even
'sent home'. Media coverage has focused on a range of 'side effects'
allegedly reported by troops who had the vaccine. However, I've seen
nothing (so far) on claims of any foetal/neonatal effects, but I've not
been following this closely.

[For those interested] other submissions to the senate investigation (most
are available online):
<http://www.aph.gov.au/Senate/committee/fadt_ctte/defhealth/index.htm>

See 'submissions received:
<http://www.aph.gov.au/Senate/committee/fadt_ctte/defhealth/submissions/sublist.htm>

--
Dr M.J. Nunn
